reviews.review_text:
Such High Energy From a head that joined the carnival in 88, this show opens with such high energy that I grieve that the show has ended in so many ways.

Jerry is just awesome with his Jack Straw riffs, and the crowd is so connected.

Audio is a bit blotto, but this source is either off the board or on excellent shot guns.  You will feel the vibe of the crowd.

A bit of Spanish guitar on Row Jimmy from Jerry.

Minglewood Blues, a bit of Rag Time Jam from Vince W.

So many roads, always a tear jerker.  No earth quake but the love is there.

Uncle John's Band is a great rendition, 2nd set.

Morning Dew is chopped, not sure if it was the tape of the show.

The show peters out a bit at the end.  Kevin from Tampa.

Warm up show Kevin from Tampa gives some great highlights and he is right.  This was the first of three shows from Tuesday to Thursday.  The boys had Monday off and they were really just getting settled in for the whole stand.  There are good moments but truthfully, it was a 2-3 on a scale of 5.  Check out the St.Patty's Day show on Wed and the finale on Thursday.  Much more rocking.  Minus Eternity.  Silly Bobby.  I still remember the Days Between-Good Lovin' with Lucy in the Sky encore as being great ending to a solid show.

sigh, Dew This was the show where Jerry fumbled the last verse of Dew and, so doing, just lost the mood and actually bailed on the finale jam.  Bob did his best to wait him out, but he wouldn't budge, so Bob finally had to shrug and launch into Sugar Mag.  Probably the lamest Jerry moment in my Dead career, the remainder of the show was irrelevant after that.  We thought he might try to make up for it the next night, and he did! opening with a nice long Shakedown and we were beaming again.

Worst Morning Dew ever Yep, this is the Morning Dew where Jerry flubs the lyrics so bad that he couldn't recover.  If my memory serves me well, ole Jer just kept noodling/drifting aimlessly until Phil stepped in with some hard riffs and the rest of the boys settled into Sugar Mag--no crescendo at the end.  Was he in a heroin stupor?  I felt embarrased for him.  The rest of the show is decent, but this run at Landover was not great in my opinion.  Lots of cops, cold weather, yellow coat security goons, people talking loudly during the show....i went to many spring 93 shows and only 2nd night Dean Dome was memorable for me in terms of music (where I believe Jerry redeemed himself with a much stronger reading of "Dew")...for me 93 was pretty spotty for great shows, but that didn't stop me from going...Eugene that year was a great experience.

Kevorkian Dew I still remember when I was there and Jerry totally pulled the plug on MORNING DEW.  I turned to my friend and said that will now be known as the Kevorkian (Dr. Kevorkian) Dew.  The rest of the show was decent, but nothing special.
